issue.title: [Feedback] Network Console will be removed in Edge 143
issue.body:
Starting with Edge 143, the Network Console tool will be removed from Edge DevTools with no replacement. As our team shifts focus toward delivering more stable features and improving alignment with Chrome, we no longer have the capacity to maintain this tool. We recommend using the REST Client extension for VS Code for API development and testing.

If this feature is important to your workflow, we encourage you to share your feedback. Strong interest could help motivate bringing it to Chromium in the future.

comment.body: I strongly oppose removing the Network Console from Edge DevTools. It is the only lightweight, built-in tool that lets developers test APIs directly inside the browser with full access to cookies, certificates, and the exact network stack our users run. Forcing us to install VS Code and an extensionâ€”or switch to Postmanâ€”adds friction and breaks quick debugging workflows. Instead of deleting the feature, please freeze it and open-source the code so the community can keep it alive while your team focuses elsewhere.

issue.title: Add new commands to enable and disable SQL Server logins
issue.body: This PR implements three new public commands for managing SQL Server login state, addressing the requirement to enable and disable SQL Server logins using the SMO Login class methods. ## New Commands ### `Enable-SqlDscLogin` Enables a SQL Server login in a SQL Server Database Engine instance. Supports two parameter sets: - **ServerObject**: Takes a server connection and login name - **LoginObject**: Takes a login object directly ```powershell # Using server object and login name $serverObject = Connect-SqlDscDatabaseEngine -InstanceName 'MyInstance' $serverObject | Enable-SqlDscLogin -Name 'MyLogin' # Using login object directly $loginObject = $serverObject | Get-SqlDscLogin -Name 'MyLogin' $loginObject | Enable-SqlDscLogin ``` ### `Disable-SqlDscLogin` Disables a SQL Server login with the same parameter set options as Enable-SqlDscLogin. ```powershell # Disable a login by name $serverObject | Disable-SqlDscLogin -Name 'MyLogin' -Force # Disable using login object $loginObject | Disable-SqlDscLogin -Force ``` ### `Test-SqlDscIsLoginEnabled` Tests whether a SQL Server login is enabled or disabled, returning a boolean value. ```powershell # Test login state by name $isEnabled = Test-SqlDscIsLoginEnabled -ServerObject $serverObject -Name 'MyLogin' # Test using login object $isEnabled = Test-SqlDscIsLoginEnabled -LoginObject $loginObject ``` ## Implementation Details - **SMO Integration**: Added `Enable()` and `Disable()` methods to the SMO Login stub for testing - **Pattern Consistency**: Commands follow the established patterns used by `Enable-SqlDscAudit` and `Disable-SqlDscAudit` - **ShouldProcess Support**: Enable and Disable commands include proper confirmation prompts with `-Force` parameter - **Localization**: Added appropriate localized strings for all user-facing messages - **Parameter Validation**: Comprehensive parameter set validation following existing command patterns ## Testing Added comprehensive unit tests covering: - Parameter set validation for all commands - Both ServerObject and LoginObject parameter sets - Refresh parameter functionality where applicable - Method invocation verification - Return value validation for Test-SqlDscIsLoginEnabled All 17 unit tests pass successfully, ensuring robust functionality and maintaining code quality standards. ## References Implementation based on the Microsoft SMO Login class documentation: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.sqlserver.management.smo.login Closes the issue requesting SQL Server login enable/disable functionality. --- ðŸ’¬ Share your feedback on Copilot coding agent for the chance to win a $200 gift card!
